Recommendations:
We recommended and it was agreed that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the required adjusting entries to reclassify tangible items, with costs below the capitalization threshold and already issued to end-users, in accordance with the illustrative entries outlined in Annex C of COA Circular No. 2024-06 dated March 14, 2024;
Require the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to correct the inaccurate JEV previously recorded for the reclassification of expendable properties;
Ensure proper documentation and monitoring of issued semi-expendable assets using the prescribed Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) to establish accountability; and
Enhance internal controls over the recording and reporting of semi-expendable items to prevent recurrence of similar issues.

Recommendations:
We recommended and Management agreed to:
Compute and recognize the appropriate depreciation expense for the subject PPE accounts following the straight line depreciation method with 5% residual value;
Ensure proper review and monitoring of PPE depreciation schedules to prevent similar omissions in the future;
Establish internal controls to ensure that depreciation is recorded accurately and consistently each reporting period; and
Prepare adjusting entries to reflect the correct balance of the affected accounts.

We recommended that Management:

As to the Technical Evaluation and Inspection results: Justification as to why the engine specification was set to point out to only one brand (tailor-fitting) and the reason for the incomplete delivery of the items specified in the contract;
Justification as to the unregistered use of the ambulance, failure to prepare the AIR, and delivery of the ambulance before the supplier’s conformed in the NTP;
Compute and impose liquidated damages against the supplier for the delayed delivery of the contract;
Submit to the audit team the Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR) and other supporting documents of the contract once completed;
Adhere to Section 4(6) of PD 1445, Sections 18 and Section 3 of Annex D of RA 9184;
Conform with DOH Administrative Order No. 2018-0001 on the licensure of land ambulances; and
Cease the use of the ambulance prior to registration with LTO, GSIS and DOH-FSRB.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the concerned officials and employees to refund the excess amount of Per Diems claimed for their respective travels;
Strictly avoid granting travelling allowances more than what is allowed;
Submit to COA the lacking documents to support the Liquidation Reports; and
Observe the complete documentary requirements in granting and liquidating cash advances, specifically for travel.

We recommended that Management:

Strictly adhere to the provisions of IPSAS 1 and COA Circular 2016-005;
Exhaust all possible remedies to collect receivables and demand liquidation of such accounts;
For receivables determined to be beyond recovery per COA Circular 2016-005, recognize impairment and facilitate the filing of request for authority to write-off following the guidelines and procedures set forth in the said Circular; and
Furnish the audit team with the updated monitoring, schedules, supporting documents, and aging of such receivable accounts.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the HRMO to submit each year to the Municipal Accountant a certified computation of the yearend balance of leave credits of officials and employees;
Accrue each year the money value of accumulated leave credits of pursuant to IPSAS 39; 
Prepare adjusting entries to accrue the money value of accumulated leave credits as of yearend and correct entries previously made and furnish COA with the JEV; and
Ensure that payment of terminal leave benefits are properly supported with valid documents before processing the payment.

We recommended that Management: 

Direct the HRMO to submit each year to the Municipal Accountant a certified computation of the yearend balance of leave credits of officials and employees;

Accrue each year the money value of accumulated leave credits of pursuant to IPSAS 39;

Prepare adjusting entries to accrue the money value of accumulated leave credits as of yearend and correct entries previously made and furnish COA with the JEV; and 

Ensure that payment of terminal leave benefits are properly supported with valid documents before processing the payment.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:

Require the HRMO to prepare a detailed and specific plan of activities per Department integrating the volume and frequency of regular and routine work to be performed and the expected output and deadline;

In issuing the authority to render overtime services, ensure that the expected output, date of completion/submission of the report, and the authorized compensation is specifically provided;

Consider the provision on the compensatory time/day-off, in lieu of the overtime pay or non-compensatory remuneration policy for overtime services pursuant to CSC and DBM JC No. 2;

Require the concerned officials to submit the DTR and a detailed accomplishment during the regular work hours, and accomplishment report and overtime work plan in all the overtime compensation claimed.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require Municipal Coordinating Team to:

Submit duly approved special project plan, indicating the nature of work assignments of the municipal officials and personnel, duties and responsibilities, and their extent of participation;

Submit accomplishment reports which specifically state the man-hours spent and the completed and accepted or accomplished deliverables;

Compute the honoraria based on the guidelines set forth under DBM Budget Circular No. 2007-02; and

Strictly comply with the provisions provided under the aforementioned circular.

We recommended that Management: 

Strictly adhere to the provisions of IPSAS 1 and COA Circular 2016-005; 

Exhaust all possible remedies to collect receivables and demand liquidation of such accounts;

For receivables determined to be beyond recovery per COA Circular 2016-005, recognize impairment and facilitate the filing of request for authority to write-off following the guidelines and procedures set forth in the said Circular; 

Furnish the audit team with the updated monitoring, schedules, supporting documents, and aging of such receivable accounts.

We recommended that Management:

Prioritize the reconciliation of balances between the accounting records and RPCPPE;

Maintain a detailed Property Ledger Card for each class of Property, Plant and Equipment that supports the balances presented in the FS. The schedule should enable the user to trace for the acquisition date and cost of an individual PPE to facilitate depreciation computation;

Provide yearly depreciation expense for the subject PPE accounts following the straight-line depreciation method with 5% residual value; and

Prepare adjusting entries, if any, to reflect the correct balance of the affected accounts.

We recommend that Management: 

Require the Municipal Development Council and the budget committee during the preparation of annual budget for 20% Development Fund to include only Programs/Projects/Activities which are feasible and could be accomplished within the target date of completion;

Implement the development projects programmed during the year as embodied in the Annual Investment /Development plan and ensure optimum utilization of the 20% Development Fund for the benefit of the constituents of the Municipality; 

Implement immediately all the projects under the continuing appropriation; and 

Ensure that all savings from completed projects and all projects which are no longer feasible and not yet implemented are considered for immediate realignment, subject to budgetary rules or reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the 20% Development Fund for re-appropriation to other development projects.

We recommended to the Management to: 

Prepare adjusting entries, as proposed below, to correct erroneous recording of fund transfers to LMP-Camiguin and furnish COA with the JEV; 
Demand Liquidation Report, whether full or partial, from the LMP-Camiguin as at year end and cause the recording of the corresponding expenses in the books;

Provide justification as to why invalid Official Receipts were accepted as proof of payment; and 

Submit the following to COA for further audit action: (1) Memorandum of Agreement on the above fund transfers (2) Valid Official Receipts for all payments to LMP-Camiguin.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:

Require the HRMO to prepare a detailed and specific plan of activities per Department integrating the volume and frequency of regular and routine work to be performed and the expected output and deadline;

In issuing the authority to render overtime services, ensure that the expected output, date of completion/submission of the report, and the authorized compensation is specifically provided;

Consider the provision on the compensatory time/day-off, in lieu of the overtime pay or non-compensatory remuneration policy for overtime services pursuant to CSC and DBM JC No. 2;

Require the concerned officials to submit the DTR and a detailed accomplishment during the regular work hours, and accomplishment report and overtime work plan in all the overtime compensation claimed; and

Refrain from granting overtime services with pay to Job Order employees.

These recommendations are without prejudice to the issuance of Notice of Suspension/Disallowance because of our audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require Municipal Coordinating Team to:

Submit duly approved special project plan, indicating the nature of work assignments of the municipal officials and personnel, duties and responsibilities, and their extent of participation;

Submit accomplishment reports which specifically state the man-hours spent and the completed and accepted or accomplished deliverables;

Compute the honoraria based on the guidelines set forth under DBM Budget Circular No. 2007-02; and

Strictly comply with the provisions provided under the aforementioned circular.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to instruct:

The officers and employees concerned for the immediate settlement of their outstanding cash advances;

The withholding of the salaries of the accountable officers until they make liquidation of their cash advances;


The Municipal Accountant to send demand letters to the employees concerned and forward the same to COA for the issuance of final demand, and initiate the filing of cases pursuant to Section 128 of PD 1445; and

The Municipal Accountant to stop the grant of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given to the officers and employees is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, and issue a certification that the employee has no outstanding cash advance for every cash advance granted.

We recommended that Management initiate the creation of the LDRRMO under the office of the Mayor.  It shall be initially composed of a local DRRM officer to be assisted by three (3) staff responsible for: 

(1) administration and training; 
(2) research and planning; and
 (3) operations and warning.  And lastly, as provided for in Section 5.5 of the said Circular, the LGU may augment the staff of the LDRRMO through any or a combination of the following options:
Designation or assignment of personnel of LGU to LDRRMO in concurrent capacities with their existing positions;

Reassignment of personnel of the LGU to the LDRRMO;

Full-time and part-time detail of existing personnel of other government agencies to the LDRRMO; and/or,

Transfer of existing vacant positions from other units to the LDRRMO.  Accordingly, such vacant positions shall be abolished and positions appropriate to the LDRRMO shall be created.

3.11	We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
Municipal Accountant to record regular purchases of inventories using the perpetual inventory method;
GSO/Municipal Treasurer to conduct regular count of inventories on hand; Prepare the required inventory reports, schedules, supplies ledger cards and stock cards; Use/accomplish the prescribed inventory forms;
Municipal Accountant to ensure coordination between the end-users and the accounting office for the submission of required reports and the proper accounting for the inventories; and
Record the expenditures to their appropriate inventory and/or expenses accounts

7.8	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the:
a.  	Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursement vouchers are supported with complete documentation;
b.  	Municipal DRRM Officer and Municipal Budget Officer to avoid the inclusion of ineligible programs, projects, and activities (PPAs), instead, prioritize PPAs for disaster preparedness, prevention, mitigation, and rehabilitation, especially during the CoVid-19 pandemic situation;
c.  	Municipal Accountant to prepare the Report on Utilization of LDRRMF properly, and the Municipal DRRM Officer to submit the same through the LDRRMC and LDC to the auditor on or before the 15th day after the end of each month.  Likewise, reflect in the report the cash assistance received from national government, other LGUs, and other sources;
d.  	Municipal Accountant to provide complete disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2012-002.

8.11	We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require Municipal Coordinating Team to:
a. 	Submit duly approved special project plan, indicating the nature of work assignments of the municipal officials and personnel, duties and responsibilities, and their extent of participation;
b. 	Submit accomplishment reports which specifically state the man-hours spent and the completed and accepted or accomplished deliverables;
c. 	Compute the honoraria based on the guidelines set forth under DBM Budget Circular No. 2007-02; and
d. 	Strictly comply with the provisions provided under the aforementioned circular.

10.9	We recommended that Municipal Mayor to require the:
a.  	Municipal Accountant to install and maintain sound internal control system over the grant of overtime pay to municipal officials and employees;
b.  	Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Engineer, and other municipal officials to perform adequate planning of work activities to ensure that regular tasks are performed during regular work hours to avoid rendition of unnecessary overtime services of municipal employees, and only services that are extremely necessary are paid by the Municipality;
c.  	All municipal officials and employees to adhere to the provisions of CSC-DBM JC No. 1, s. 2015

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to instruct:

a) The officers and employees concerned for the immediate settlement of their outstanding cash advances;

b) The withholding of the salaries of the accountable officers until they make liquidation of their cash advances;

c)   The Municipal Accountant to send demand letters to the employees concerned and forward the same to COA for the issuance of final demand, and initiate the filing of cases pursuant to Section 128 of PD 1445; and

d) The Municipal Accountant to stop the grant of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given to the officers and employees is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, and issue a certification that the employee has no outstanding cash advance for every cash advance granted.

We recommend the following courses of actions to facilitate the recording of the 38 lots in the books of accounts and establish ownership:

The Local Chief Executive should instruct the Municipal Treasurer to retrieve all the Deed of Sale or Deed of Donation or any document that will establish the ownership from Offices such as the Register of Deeds, Department of Environment and Natural Resources and other Offices;

The Municipal Accountant should record in the books all the Lots based on the Tax Declaration on file with the Municipal Assessor at fair market value;

As mandated in Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386, the Local Chief Executive shall ensure that all the lots should be registered under the Torrens Title System and safeguarded from squatters, unlawful occupants and the like.

